flowchart TD
%% Mikado graph for Issue #4 — Kernel.@/1 override compatibility
%%
%% Bond's `use Bond` does `import Kernel, except: [@: 1]` then `import Bond`,
%% placing Bond's @pre/@post/@invariant/@doc clauses and a catch-all
%% `defmacro @attr` (which forwards to `Kernel.@/1`) in scope.
%%
%% Two separate concerns under test:
%%   A. Does the catch-all correctly forward standard Elixir attributes
%%      (@derive, @enforce_keys, typespecs, accumulating attrs, etc.)?
%%   B. What happens when another library also overrides @/1?
%%      (Conflict: last `use` wins; Bond's catch-all routes to Kernel,
%%       bypassing the other lib's interception. Order matters.)
%%
%% Arrows point from a goal to its prerequisites. Leaves (green) have no
%% further prerequisites and are safe to start first. Depth-first per Mikado:
%% pick a leaf, finish it, keep tests green, commit, repeat.
%%
%% Cross-library test uses Norm (`only: :test` dep) as the conflict counterpart.
%% Norm's `Norm.Contract` uses the IDENTICAL technique to Bond — `import Kernel,
%% except: [@: 1]`, a specific `@{:contract, _, expr}` clause, and a catch-all
%% forwarding to `Kernel.@(unquote(other))`. Originally I considered a synthetic
%% `FakeAttrLib`, but Norm is the real-world twin: testing against it validates
%% the exact conflict shape that real users will hit and lets the FAQ name a
%% concrete library. Norm has no extra runtime deps (only optional stream_data,
%% which Bond already has).
%%
%% Empirical finding from Step 2: combining `use Bond` and `use Norm` in the same
%% module fails to compile with `function @/1 imported from both Bond and
%% Norm.Contract, call is ambiguous`, REGARDLESS of `use` ordering. Elixir does
%% NOT do "last import wins" — both imports end up at the same scope level and
%% Elixir flags the call site as ambiguous. The conflict is loud (clear compile
%% error pointing at the first `@`-using line), not silent. Recommended workaround:
%% split into separate modules, one per contract library.

    G(["**Goal**<br/>Issue #4 closed: @/1 override compatibility verified;<br/>attribute forwarding + cross-library interaction tested;<br/>compatibility note documented in FAQ"])

    G --> S4["4. Add 'Compatibility with @/1-overriding libraries' section to guides/faq.md.<br/>Document the empirical finding: combining `use Bond` with another @/1-<br/>overriding lib (e.g. Norm) in one module fails at compile time with a<br/>clear 'ambiguous import' error, regardless of ordering. Recommend the<br/>split-modules workaround, with a concrete code example.<br/><b>#4-compat-guide</b>"]

    S4 --> S3["3. Cross-library conflict tests (test/bond/norm_compat_test.exs).<br/>Smoke-test each standalone fixture works (BondValidator raises<br/>Bond.PreconditionError; NormValidator raises Norm.MismatchError on bad<br/>input). Use Code.compile_string/1 to demonstrate that combining `use<br/>Bond` and `use Norm` in one module fails with the ambiguous-import<br/>error in both orderings.<br/><b>#4-cross-lib-tests</b>"]

    S4 --> S1["1. Attribute forwarding fixtures + tests<br/>(test/support/bond_test/attr_compat.ex + test/bond/attr_compat_test.exs).<br/>Modules combining `use Bond` with: @derive, @enforce_keys, @spec/@type/<br/>@typep/@opaque/@callback, accumulating custom attrs, @external_resource,<br/>@behaviour. Assert each attribute is present and has the expected value.<br/><b>#4-forwarding-tests</b>"]

    S3 --> S2["2. Add Norm as `only: :test` dep + standalone fixtures<br/>(test/support/bond_test/norm_compat.ex). Two single-library modules<br/>demonstrating the split-modules workaround: BondValidator (use Bond +<br/>@pre) and NormValidator (use Norm + @contract). Originally planned as<br/>'both orderings of combined use', but step-2 compilation revealed the<br/>combination is ambiguous in either order, so the fixtures became<br/>standalone modules.<br/><b>#4-norm-dep-and-fixtures</b>"]

    classDef leaf fill:#e7f5e7,stroke:#2e7d32,stroke-width:2px;
    class S1,S2 leaf;

    style G fill:#90EE90
    style S1 fill:#90EE90
    style S2 fill:#90EE90
    style S3 fill:#90EE90
    style S4 fill:#90EE90
